ness to the Eisen\nhower Administration. He may\nbe leaving the scene at any\ntime between now and next\nyear\u2019s congressional elections.\nA powerful group of Repub\nlicans is now arrayed against\nthe big-farmer, low-support po\nlicies of Benson, and heartly\ndisagree with him that things\nare satisfactory in the field of\nfarm policy and progress.\nThis has happened before\nbut not on such a scale. Each\ntime the crisis has occurred in\nthe past President Eisenhower\nhas stuck loyally by his agricul\nture chief. However, there are\ni now other people to be con\nsidered, rather than Mr. Eisen\nhower\u2019s political neck and Mr.\nI Benson himself.\nSome Republican Congress-\nwith new things that make driving hap\npier and riding smoother.\nJust try one! Power ranges from\nthe budget-minded 145-h.p. Blue-\nFlame 6 to Chevy\u2019s radical 280-h.p.\nSuper Turbo-Thrust VB.* Delrays,\nlike other models, have a new Full\nCoil suspension\u2014a softer, road-level\ning ride. You can have a real air ride*\nto make the going even smoother\u2014and\nOverdrive* to make it even thriftier.\nSee all that\u2019s new at your Chevrolet\ndealer\u2019s. *Optional at extra cost.\nGADSDEN COUNTY TIMES, QUINCY, FLORIDA, THURSDAY, NOVEMBER 28.1957\nmen, up for reelection next year J\nin the agricultural areas, know\nthat carrying Bendon around 1\ntheir necks is like carrying an\nalbatross and that this might,\ndefeat them, if their Democra- i\ntic opposition is formidable, j\nIn addition, the presidential j\ncandidate of the Republican\nParty in 1960 will not have\nEisenhower\u2019s gre^t strength\nwith the American people and i\nwill have to see to it that all\nhandicaps, which might prevent j\nsuccess at the polls in a nation\nal election, are removed.\nBy all odds, and admittedly\non all sides, Benson is a politi\ncal liability to the Republicans.\nThere are many Democrats who\nhope he will remain in office,\nbecause they know the value to\ntheir party if he is on the scene\nto be \u201cused\u201d in coming elec\ntions.\nBut even the Republicans\nwho support Benson, for the\nmost part know he is a liability.\nEven those who believe in his\nfarm philosophies, and his the-\nories, admit he is a political\nliability. They, however, believe\nthat he should be retained in\noffice, and a considerable group\nof supporters have again voiced\na willingness to stick by him.\nNevertheless, the time seems\nto be inevitably nearing when\nMr. Eisenhower will have to re\nmtfve Benson for the good of\nthe party, including the 1960\npresidential nominee and the\nlarge number of congressmen\nand senators facing election\nfights next year and in 1960.\nThese practical politicians\nsaw the handwriting the\nwall in Wisconsin. All the ex\nplantions, all the excuses and\nall the leveling of blame on tne\nDemocrats can\u2019t hide the farm\nrecession and the squeeze of the\nlittle farmer. That is real.\nHow much spending is going\nup in the coming fiscal year is\na question of lively debate in\nWashington but it is ex dent\nthat spending will increase.\nFirst estimates are that the mil\nitary budget will be hiked by\ntwo billion dollars, to approxi\nmately $4O billions. There are\nthose who c that this is too\nmuch, that money will be saved\nelsewhere in the budget.\nBut old-hand politicians ar\ngue that not much monjy will\nbe saved in the non-military\nfields and that when the com\nmittees, expected to do the\nchopping, get down to bare\nfacts, they won\u2019t be able to chop\nvery much.\nQuantity Rights Reserved K A A A\nPrices Good K/vylA/V/l\nThru. Saturday, Nov. 30.\nI B 1 W __ wbN I\nI1 V Pur. White ^7 I\n|SNOWDRIFTg\nbUb\u00ae 4 $3 ft 9c\nI Bruce Grapefruit C M A A W\nIJUICE B^*l^\nI Astor Vac. Pak. 888 MM Dixie Darling Long Grain MM MM\nCOFFEE 59 c RICE 3 s 39'\nNew Blue HM MM Superbrand Bag jh MM\nIRINSO 59' COFFEE 49'\nI Cabin Home MM MM 41 Dixie Darling MM MM fl\nIMEAL slb 29' Bread 2 ^29',\nFresh (Not Frozen) Gov't. Inspected MM M^\nPork Loin ROAST 39'\n